solution.p:
Applying the power and constant multiple rules, we have

  \frac{d}{dx}\left[ (-1)^{k} \frac{x^{2k}}{(2k)!} \right] = (-1)^{k} \frac{1}{(2k)!} \cdot (2k)x^{2k-1}
.
Using the fact that \frac{2k}{(2k)!} = \frac{1}{(2k-1)!}, we have 

  \frac{d}{dx}\left[ (-1)^{k} \frac{x^{2k}}{(2k)!} \right] = (-1)^{k} \frac{1}{(2k-1)!} \cdot x^{2k-1}
.

Since we know the series for -\sin(x), we find the series for \sin(x) by taking its opposite.  Doing so,

   \sin(x) = -(-\sin(x)) \amp= - \left( \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} (-1)^{k} \frac{x^{2k-1}}{(2k-1)!} \right)\amp 
                         \amp= \sum_{k=1}^{\infty} (-1)^{k-1} \frac{x^{2k-1}}{(2k-1)!}  

In the sum, observe that when k = 1, it follows that 2k - 1 = 1.  If we recognize that odd integers can be represented either as 2k-1 or 2k+1, it's possible to re-index the series in sigma notation and write

  \sin(x) = -(-\sin(x)) = \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} (-1)^{k} \frac{x^{2k+1}}{(2k+1)!}
.
